<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Eating corpses can be extremely hazardous to one's health -- especially when the corpse in question is a Unique. Eating from a corpse in ToME can grant beneficial effects, hurt you badly... or even kill you. Some effects may be beneficial <em>if</em> you survive your dinner. So, let the diner beware! <hr>
 <ol>
<li>
<a href="#head-2c1c91ef2c364e57a166fe749853e2a1f8f33e7a">Effects from just hacking corpses</a></li>
<li>
<a href="#head-40c4a79035b156a231ffdafaa63e8c2d77263b55">Effects from eating hacked meats</a></li>
<li>
<a href="#head-6ae415a59f40f715f2c01e98eac39c560e15df09">Effects from eating non-unique corpses</a></li>
<li>
<a href="#head-299610eb0d0d805e843fa6e9c62f11ca216a66cd">Effects from eating unique corpses</a></li>
<li>
<a href="#head-ff11f0da0a4cd245270f188d8a7299b4084d0328">Chatter</a></li>
</ol>

 <hr>
 <h2 id="head-2c1c91ef2c364e57a166fe749853e2a1f8f33e7a">Effects from just hacking corpses</h2>
Hacking a red dragon bat corpse gave resist fire.  Depending on the corpse weight, you can get temp resist to fire, cold, acid and/or electricity just from hacking a corpse.  All the bad stuff that can happen when you eat a corpse can occur when you hack one too. <p>
In general, hacking the corpse of a monster that has a breath attack will release a <em>tremendously</em> powerful attack against you, of the damage type caused by that breath.  The amount of damage caused by the release depends on the corpse's weight, <em>not</em> on the monster's level, hit points, etc.  The amount of damage you take from this attack may be <em>much</em> greater than the amount you would have taken from the monster's breath while it was alive.  Immunity or double resistance to the element in question is strongly advised. 
</p>
<h2 id="head-40c4a79035b156a231ffdafaa63e8c2d77263b55">Effects from eating hacked meats</h2>
You get food value from eating hacked meats, but nothing else. <p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: You sure about that?  I seem to remember otherwise, but I may be mistaken. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Yup! I'm sure. I doublechecked the food value just now. And I'm positive you don't get additional effects: I had Ulfang's corpse (see below) and tried hacking him, as I thought it'd be quite handy to have a pile of meats along for the resists. Eating them did nothing (other than getting full.) 
</p>
<p>
Could it be that that was what the "cure meat" thing (which doesn't work) was supposed to do? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./GreyCat">GreyCat</a></strong>: Curing meat decreases the spoilage counter, or something like that.  Let's see... 
</p>

    <ul>

 
<pre>        case SV_POTION_SALT_WATER:
                {
                        q = "You salt the meat.";
                        cure = 200 * num;
        ...
        /* Cure the meat */
        o_ptr-&gt;timeout += cure / o_ptr-&gt;number;</pre>
    </ul>


<p>
Over in dungeon.c, there's a piece of code that should "decay" the meat.  I don't know whether there are bugs in this code, since I haven't done much with meat myself. 
</p>
<h2 id="head-6ae415a59f40f715f2c01e98eac39c560e15df09">Effects from eating non-unique corpses</h2>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 Dragons, dragonflies, dragon bats 
</p>
</li>

        <ul>

        <li>
<p>
 Red, blue, green, white, black: Resistance to the relevant element(s). 
</p>
</li>

        </ul>


    <li>
<p>
 Aether hounds: RBase, RPois, <a class="nonexistent" href="./ProtEvil">ProtEvil</a>.  Still tastes bad, though <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Patriarch summons several pets, usually half decent ones! <strong><a href="./ArcherElf">ArcherElf</a></strong> 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Knight Templar: RBase, RPois, <a class="nonexistent" href="./ProtEvil">ProtEvil</a>, summon pet angel (if the current dungeon permits). 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<h2 id="head-299610eb0d0d805e843fa6e9c62f11ca216a66cd">Effects from eating unique corpses</h2>
Base Uniques: 
    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 Azog, King of the Uruk-Hai:  Resist poison. 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Ar-Pharazon the Golden:  Summon pets. 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Beorn, the Shape-Changer:  No effects. 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Boldor, King of the Yeeks:  Resist acid; summon one pet. 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Bolg, Son of Azog:  Resist poison. 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Brodda, the Easterling:  No effects 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
